segments.text: Once those first semester midterm grades come out, reality sort of sticks in.
So the pendulum starts to swing back.
Say, wait a minute, I'm spending too much time over here doing all this other stuff that's not going to have any bearing on my life really at all.
I mean, it will, but not as much.
I better start putting my time in some books.
So I stuck for the next three months.
I worked real hard, managed to bring it up to about a C average I think at the end of the first semester.
Then I got into the Texas Maritime business and that really, my life changed.
Let's give us a break.
Let's back up a little though.
Fall semester,
going to first football games.
What was that like?
Oh, that was awesome.
The march in, I still get choked up when the flag comes by.
I love parades.
I still think that the Corps cadets at Texas A&M have the best drill of any place in the world.
As a matter of fact, the Corps really reminds me, now that I've spent 32 years in the Naval service and have dealt a lot with the Marines, my son-in-law is a Marine captain,
that it's an awful lot like the Marine Corps.
The camaraderie, the, you know, just the appearance and the way we march.
If you look at any, all the academies, if you look at them when they come marching in, there's just no comparison in Texas A&M, none whatsoever.
Did you and your buddies as fish, did you all try any good bull at games?
I'm trying to think.
You know, we were pretty straight, I think.
I don't recall, you know, we were always, you know, we'd have beer and that kind of stuff, but, you know, we'd have dates, you know, but I don't recall.
Did you have dates as a freshman?

Not here at the campus, but, you know, when we'd go to march-ins and things, there was always a guy that was from that part of the town, and, you know, he'd introduce us to some gals, and, you know, they always liked to see guys in uniforms.
That was still kind of popular.
So I can remember...
remember doing that.
We had a guy named Jerry Buttrell was my executive officer in E2 and his sister was about my age.
I remember going to Beaumont and visiting her.
So it was fun fulfilled.
I do recall though some other stuff.
Sonny Cantanzaro had a, I want to say he had a Chevy, like a 56, 57 Chevy.
And he was from Beaumont and just a wonderful guy.
And I think he was the only one in our group that had a car.

And so we'd get in his car and we'd manage to, I'm really telling stories here, we'd manage to get his ID or my ID or somebody's ID where you could move some numbers around, glue them back on, and it looked like you were 21.
So we'd go out and buy those big bottles of beer, Pearl I think it was in those days.
And I can remember going out here to,
towards Navasota someplace, and we'd just pull off the side of the road and jump on the fence post there and sit there and drink that beer and tell stories and stuff.
And there would be guys about every four or five miles doing that.

Well, we were sitting there, we weren't, you know, we were not throwing the bottles around or anything, but evidently another crowd up the road was throwing bottles and the sheriff showed up, thought we were the ones doing it.
And I can remember running out into the woods, hiding in a thistle, the guys walking around with the flashlight,
He had the car, but he didn't have us.
And, you know, he didn't do anything with the car.
It was the dirtiest thing I've ever seen.
I guess he didn't have a problem with cars or whatever.
And we managed to get back and said, well, we've got to not do that again.
So we started going out here to the Brazos and drinking.
That was our little place.
I remember jumping off the sand cliffs out there and that kind of stuff.
At the football games, were the sophomores smoking cigars in those years?
No, not that I recall.
See, in other years,
Big deal was sophomores smoked lots of cigars and blew the smoke in the freshman's face.
I don't recall that.
I don't recall that ever happening.
Court trips as a freshman.
Did you make those trips?
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
What was it like?
It was great fun.
You know, four or five of us, six of us, eight of us, a hundred of us, however many we needed would chip in and get one room and...
And again, we'd have dates, and it was just a lot of fun.
Generally, as I recall, since my grandparents lived in Texas, that would give me a break to run up to Sherman.
So I would just go up there, sometimes just do the game, and then run up to Sherman and spend the weekend up there.
Because most of the time, it seemed to me like I spent a good deal of my time restricted, except for those kinds of things.
Did you ever hitchhike?
Oh, absolutely.
In fact, I still have my bag.
That's a good question.
I have a Samsonite little overnight bag that's got Texas Aggies on it.
Never had any problems hitchhiking.
Never even thought about it.
and until, you know, years later.
And everybody stuck by the rules.
You didn't up, you didn't try to, what was the slang word?
where you would try to not upstage, but instead of being at the right place, you'd try to be upstream.
Upstream?
No, I don't recall any of that.
It seems to me like you just walked out here, stuck your thumb out.
Everybody was helpful.
Yeah, everybody was helpful.
It seems to me that, as I recall,
Generally, it was hitchhiking to go from here to Galveston.

You know, I remember my, Terry Archer and I, his grandparents lived down in Texas City, so we'd just go out here, and there weren't a lot of folks going that direction, it didn't seem like, and you'd just go out here and put your thumb out, and pretty soon somebody would come along and give you a ride down there.
Alright, again, that first fall, do you remember going to Silver Taps the first time?
Oh, yeah, that was, I do, and that, and it still is, we've done it, in fact, as a battle group commander,

I got all the Aggies together on Kitty Hawk, or yeah, it was Kitty Hawk, and we had a muster, you know, right there on Kitty Hawk, which I think was, they showed it in some magazines or something, but yeah, that was really an eye-opener to me, you know, and I still get tears in my eyes when those kinds of things happen, because you really see what people have done, and you think about what they've done, and now, of course, as I
As I get the magazine, I see that, you know, my classmates are starting to die and so forth.
And, you know, it causes you to reflect a little bit.
Bonfire.
What did you do on Bonfire?
Well, we, the F word, the trees, you know, went out and it seemed to me like the.
About how long did y'all work on this?
Oh, goodness.
It was a, it, I want to, I mean, it went on forever, it seemed to me like.
Of course, you know, time is funny in those days.
I don't remember how many days it really took, but I can remember going out and,
And out on the weekend, I mean, it felt like a military operation.
We were all in our fatigues and go out and we'd carry the logs out and load them.

and then come back and help them stack and of course as a fish you're just a gopher you know and then of course we had in those days we had foxholes and stuff out around the perimeter and we all had watches that we had to stand to make sure that you know nobody came in there and it was it was a military operation nobody ever tried to during your no i don't recall anybody trying at least not on not that i never heard i never heard of anybody trying to come in and light it but
But gosh, you wouldn't want it to.
And was this on Drillfield or Duncan?
No, it was over behind Duncan.
It was over behind Duncan.
And I guess it seemed to me like that's where they'd held them for years.
I guess about in the vicinity of the Bush Library, huh?
No, no, no, Bush Library is way over here.
Oh, way over here, okay.
Well, it's over in that area.
And were there any accidents that you remember?
Oh, you know, people getting whacked by chainsaws and dropping, but nothing serious, getting splinters and that kind of stuff, but I don't recall any.
You know, and I really thought we had, it looked to me like it was just a plan that had been executed year after year after year and had been handed down from Bubba to Bubba to Bubba,
And of course, I do recall that we wanted to build it bigger than anybody else.
But we didn't build it by stack.
We built it by how tall we could get the center pole up.
And so it was a little bit, you know, and I want to say it was only two tiers in those days.
I think you're about right.
And then we had this big tall, and I can remember a toilet sitting up at the top of it or something.
And, but yeah, that was it.
That, I recall that as being really a lot of fun.
And it was hard work, but you're out in the woods, it was crisp, and, you know,
Everybody, you know, it didn't matter who it was, freshman up through, you know, through the seniors.
Everybody was involved, and we weren't getting yelled at a lot.
You know, it was really a neat operation, I thought, very professionally done, as I recall.
All right, and you go home Christmas, and when do you begin to feel...

fairly sure you're not going to go somewhere else when did you quit oh that i i tell you what that happened uh that happened pretty early on because uh i i still sort of thought i was going to go to the naval academy and uh but uh but i got down here and i just i liked what i saw i wasn't happy with my grades that was kind of bothering me a little bit i went home and that and christmas didn't have a part in this my dad was stationed off it and uh right before we left for christmas vacation down here
We were wearing the pinks and greens, and we had a horrible rain.
Actually, it was at a football game, I guess it was.
I didn't realize how that worsted wool would shrink, and that would be a sidelight to the stories, but keep that in mind.
But basically, we put on our khakis and went out here, went up to Sherman, got on a train, Terry Archer and I did, and rode a train from Denison, Texas to Omaha, Nebraska, just a couple of seats.
And as a matter of fact, there were some other kids on there from North Texas, some of the girls that we went to high school with in Bellevue.
And then each year, of course, I had my uniform, my pinks and greens with me, because the officer's club always throws a party for all the military schools.
But, gosh, I took mine out, put them on, and the daggum things were up around my knees, and we tried to stretch them.
And I can remember having them way down low.
Of course, with the blouse on, you couldn't see that they were low slung, you know, as long as you didn't get down with the pockets.
I finally managed to get them down.
But all my friends had gone to the Air Force Academy, the Naval Academy, West Point.
They all showed up, and
And it was, you know, they kind of looked down their nose a little bit at me.
But I think once we told some stories, that all changed.
But I had no intentions after that of ever leaving the system, the Texas A&M system.
All right.
And then now, describe how you shifted into the... Well, we had this friend of mine by the name of Bob Hedeman, who is now a harbor pilot up in Baltimore.
And...
Bob was in our company and a really nice guy.
And one day I was talking about how I really wanted to get into the Navy and all that.
He says, well, you know, there's a school starting up down in Galveston that's part of the Texas A&M system.
And it's got Navy ROTC in it.
I said, well, holy mackerel, that's what I want to do.
And it's on the ocean, and yeah, we've got a training ship.
In the summer of 65, it was going to be the first time the ship went to sea, the Texas Clipper.
And it's a big passenger ship, and the cadets will do all the work on it and navigate it and operate it and all that.
And I said, well, man, that sounds really neat.
And I can get a commission.
Yeah, you can get a commission.
So I went down, talked to the folks.
And of course, you went here the first year.
Actually, I guess the first class went here the first two years and then went down there.
So I changed my major the second semester.
And officially it was named Marine Transportation.
Well, officially it was named the Texas Maritime Academy.
No, no, but the major.
The major was Marine Transportation.
Marine Engineering and Marine Transportation were the two degrees that you got.

And so they took a look and they said, well, you know, you've got to really do some studying here because you've got to make up some Spanish and there were some other courses that they had, spherical trigonometry and things that have to do with navigation that I hadn't taken.
But anyway, I got into it, and it really sparked my interest, and all of a sudden my academics went up.
I guess the moral to the story is when you really figure out what it is you want to do, it just makes so much difference in the way you go about your business.
So we got into it, and then...
There was an application.
It was just like changing a major because it was part of the system.
And about when did you learn you'd been accepted?
It was fairly quick.
It was one of those deals that you kind of fall into.
They were looking for folks.
So it wasn't hard to do that.
They were looking for people.
Did any of your buddies, any of your outfit buddies, give you a hard time?
Yeah, it was not.
Some of them, I'm sure, thought it was, well, he's going to be here for just a few months and then he's going down to Galveston and we'll never see him again.
Well, that's not true because we...
The only thing we didn't do was reside in the same dorm, even though it was distance apart.
We probably saw folks up here as much as a fellow does that lives in another dorm, or if you live on the other side of the school.
We came up for all the march-ins.
We wore Navy uniforms.
In fact, we even tried to figure out a way to wear boots, you know, but it looked too Gestapo-like, so we didn't do that with a blue uniform.
You finished the spring semester.
And we wore a little different.
We wore a Texas Maritime Academy patch, the same uniform, but the Texas Maritime Academy patch on it.
But you finished the spring semester up here.
Yes, sir.
What did you do that summer?
Well, that summer we went to school.
We went down.
We left here for about two weeks and drew all of our Navy uniforms, which we had to get tailored and all that, and then showed up down in Galveston in June, early June.
They had just brought this ship called, it was the old Excambium,
and they'd brought it in from the Boneyard and it was over in Todd's Shipyard in Galveston but it was a mess.
That ship was an absolute mess.
They'd put tar on the teak decks so it was just this gooey stuff.
They hadn't put anything down to protect the decks so we were trying to do that.
The engines were a mess.

I can remember Bob Hederman and I then roomed together, the fellow that introduced me to this thing, and we had really a pretty nice stateroom on the ship but no air conditioning, no flow of air whatsoever.
The toilets didn't work.
The showers didn't work.
It was literally a mess.
Of course, they're making us wear whites and all this.
Then they decided it was too hot to stay on the ship, so they bussed us over to Fort Crockett where the oceanography folks live.
We had half of that building down there at Fort Crockett.
They put army cots up on the breezeway on the second deck there.
That's where we all started.
How many were there in your...
There were probably, I want to say about 30 of us.
And it was like being a fish all over again because now you really expect to come in and be an upperclassman.
Well, there wasn't any underclassmen.
The juniors and seniors were just, you know, they had blood dripping from their

from their mouths to get hold of us, so we went right back through another freshman year again, push-ups, set-ups, and, you know, it was a complete freshman year again, as far as I, not quite as bad, but it was pretty interesting.
They gave us a hard time.
And generally describe the student body.
They're all male?
All male, all folks interested in going to sea.
Pretty well all Texans?
There were...
I'd say 90% Texans.
The Fort, let me just kind of explain the campus a little bit.
The Fort Crockett was an old army post.
The San Luis Hotel actually used to not, was not there and they had that gun emplacement out there.
And so they had these beautiful old buildings that they built back in the 30s.
And the school, you walked right out and it was just a, it was a big grass front area with a flag pole.
And then you walk about another 200 yards and you were on the beach.
And it was all, in those days in Galveston, there wasn't much down there.
Coast Guard was down that way, and that was about it.
And then stuff that was associated with oceanography.
The class size was, I guess, all told, there were probably 100, maybe 60 to 100, you know, coming and going.
We had some former military folks who were there on the GI Bill that went through all the stuff that resided at home.
Some of them were married, which we found a little bit strange.
The building had been fixed up really nice.
The class size was just wonderful.
I mean, it was 10, 15 people in a class.
I carried 21, 22 hours the whole time I was down there.
And I never felt, you know, like I couldn't handle it.
And then, of course, in the summer, you asked about, once we got the ship fixed, you know, it took about three fall starts to get her to sea that year.
Now, having commanded a couple of ships and looking back on that experience,
Boy, I'll tell you what, we were lucky.
We were lucky that we didn't have a major, major conflagration on that ship.
But we got her to sea, went to Halifax, crossed the North Atlantic, and got in some good storms up there.
And actually, we lost our power a couple of times and made it over from Halifax over to, I can see we went into Dublin, Ireland, and then down to Bournemouth, England.
into the Canary Islands and then back through Bermuda and back into Galveston.
Now, you were hoping for a career in the Navy.
I wanted a career in the Navy.
What about your shipmates?
Well, it kind of varied.
Most of them wanted to go to sea.
And the Merchant Marines in those days, we were really hurting for Merchant Marine officers.
And Vietnam was going on.
They had some 500 ships that weren't crewed enough to even get out of port.
So the unions were going strong.
Merchant Marines was going strong.
The money was phenomenal.
I made more, my first year out of school in 68, 69, I made about $50,000, which was just amazing.
Yeah, I paid more in taxes my first year out of college than I made my first year in the Navy, which really confused my wife a little bit.
So you finish your first year here.
Go down there.
Summer.
Ship out pretty well all summer?
All summer long.
It was about a, I want to say 90 day.
Then come back there for the fall.
A few days off and did the fall semester.
Then how often did you all come back up here then?
All the ball games.
We marched in at all the ball games.
You came up on buses?
No, actually we came up individually as a matter of fact.
And by then, folks, you know, we had, that's an interesting question.
I think, and there might have been a bus, but most of, you know, we all had classmates that had cars, so it didn't, transportation wasn't a problem.
And hitchhiked, we hitchhiked.
What uniform did you wear?
We wore the Navy.
We wore Navy blues or whites, depending on what time of year it was.
Official Navy, not an A&M style.
No, they were official Navy.
In fact, I wore them until I got spatta.
They didn't fit me.
I wore them through flight training.
It was the same exact uniform as the Navy wears.
Was there an Aggie, College Station Aggie nickname for you guys?
What did they call you?
What the heck were we?
Sea cadets.
That's a good question.
It's in the annual.
I just can't remember what it is.
I would think they must have done something.
They did, yeah.
But we never had any, we were always accepted.
Where did you, when you were up here for a football game, where did you sleep?
Motels.
Oh, okay.
And then we had some upperclassmen that had come back up here for courses or whatever.
So there was ways to, that was never an issue either.
Sometimes we just came up for the game and went home.
I can remember doing that.
Back down in Galveston, did you all transplant any A&M traditions?
Oh, all of them.
Everything.
We wore all that.
We'd come up here for silver taps and all that kind of stuff.
But down there, we wore all the same belt buckles.
Even with the Navy uniform, we wore a white belt.
We did all the traditional, as much as we could, wearing those uniforms.
So then after your sophomore year, what do you do in the summer?
I would go and cruise again.
Same thing, carried almost like 12 hours in summer school.
But your job kind of changes on the cruise, on the training ship.

Instead of being just like an able-bodied seaman and chipping and painting and all that kind of stuff, the second cruise you move up into standing watches in the engine room and up on the bridge and you start signaling, you start navigating.
and doing all that kind of stuff.
So it was a nice flow.
And did you and your buddies think that you were real Texas Aggies?
Oh, absolutely.
Absolutely.
There was never any doubt about that.
General Rudder came down several times.
We had our picture made right out here.

you know just like uh... just like if you open the book you can't tell the difference uh... who was the uh... the chief executive officer of the maritime it was it was bennett dotson captain bm dotson in those days and then uh... uh... a uh... coast guard two star by the name of craig came in describe dotson he was a uh...
We called him the old rattlesnake.
He looked the part of a naval officer.
He was gray-headed and just looked the part.
A nice man, a wonderfully nice man.
Had this vision along with some other folks down there and got it aligned with Texas A&M, which was the smartest thing they ever did.
And then went to the state.
The state had already obligated some money to build a Texas maritime school
But they just hadn't done much about it.
And, of course, the Maritime Administration had money that they could give from a government source.
And he orchestrated all that, did a great job.
Now, he, there were things that, you know, he was in the Navy, ship handling in the Navy is, I'll be blunt, I think it's terrible.
And having done a lot of ship handling,
And I remember in, where was it, in Halifax, or no, in Los Palmos and Canary Islands, we started bringing the ship away from the dock, and the gangplank still looked up.
So, you know, there were some of those.
We dropped the anchor in Bermuda, and everybody tried to tell him that, you know, this isn't the place to anchor, and the anchor went all the way to its bitter end, if you will.
So, you know, he had those kinds of things that kind of gave him the name Old Rattlesnake.
But he was a heck of a nice man and really was a guy that kind of put the whole thing together.
What was it like to be a college student in Galveston on the island?
Well, you know, we were working so hard.
I love Galveston.
In fact, we have a house down there that we share.
We spend our time halfway between Florida and Texas.
We're both places.
And Galveston was a wonderful, just a wonderful place to live.
A lot of stuff going on and a lot of ships, a lot of activities.
And, of course, you're doing what you want to do.
And, you know, you've got a big machinery you're dealing with and everything.
And it was a great place.
And we weren't as remote.
In those days, Texas A&M was pretty remote, and there weren't a whole lot of things to do.
Down there, there was always something to do.
And it was really a lot of fun.
I would think that Galveston would be a marvelous college.
Oh, it was.
It was just a one.
Of course, we'd do things like to get a date.

We'd go down to the nurse's dorm at the University of Texas Medical Center down there, and we'd just dial a bunch of room numbers, and then we'd hide behind the couch, and when they'd come down, we'd kind of call out the ones we wanted.
I mean, really some crazy things, but we had a good time.
We had a good time.
Where were some wild places in Galveston?
Oh, that whole Strand area down there was wild.
There were a bunch of places down there you could get in trouble.
Was the Balinese room still going there?
The Balinese room was still going on.
In fact, we...
Going on in the sense that we had a couple of our, we call ourselves the Cadet Corps down there, and we had a couple of Corps parties in there, Christmas parties and things.
So it was going.
Because once upon a time that was.
Gambling.
Yeah.
It wasn't when I was down there.
And, of course, the Flagship Hotel was a place.
It was always fun to go to the Flagship Hotel and have a party because you'd get in the elevator and,
Of course, wearing a Navy uniform, they'd look at you and think you're the elevator operator and say, give me the fifth floor, will you please?
Those kinds of things went on all the time.
I remember Stuart Udall landed.
We graduated the class of 67 down there six months early because of the necessity to get officers into the Merchant Marines.
Some of those guys had to come back up here and finish class up to get their diploma.
But they graduated them early.
So I was very fortunate to be, I was picked as the Corps Commander down there in January.
So I think I had that job longer than anybody.
So I had it all through that last part of my junior year and all of my senior year.
So it was kind of interesting.
Describe, what was it like to be the Commander?
Well, it was interesting.
One of the first things we did was get our code of conduct.
more in line with what they have here at Texas A&M at the main campus because I thought we ought to be closer aligned.
I had a great staff that Cecil Eubanks and others that worked on that.
We also took a good hard look at the hazing part.
I just
in my heart of hearts, and I could do it because I'd been hazed pretty heavily, I just didn't see what that brought to the equation.
I felt there were other ways to stress people and not beat them.
You know, I just didn't think that was a thing one person ought to do to another.
So we knocked all that stuff out.
We still did pushups and setups and that kind of stuff, but we knocked all that.
We put our emphasis on appearance and uniforms and academics and I think that was probably about the right thing to do.
And you reported to whom?
I reported to the executive officer, a fellow by the name of Philbrick, who's retired and lives down in Corpus Christi.
And he was really a nice man.
He'd been at the Maine Maritime Academy and came down.
And, you know, he allowed us to carry on our Texas A&M.
He didn't understand them all, but he allowed us to carry most of our conditions on.
When did you acquire your nickname?
That was done in combat in Vietnam after I went to flight training.
I think everybody called me Pick in those days, pretty much.
Curiosity, I have a sidelined interest in how names develop.
What does Pick-A-Vance mean to you?
We've never traced it too far because we think there might be some questionable lineage there, but that aside, we think it goes back to the Norman invasion.

and you know back as you knowing names the second names are in those days were non-existent and when they started having second names it became a pretty much what you did we think that it comes from picks advance from the from the picks from the invasion and the interesting thing is there's two spellings my name is p-i-c-k-a-v-a-n-c-e which is the protestant spelling or so it seems to be
The Catholic spelling is P-I-C-K-V-A-N-C-E.
So my name in English is pronounced Pickovance, and the Catholic version is Pickvance.
And did you and your buddies did feel like you were Aggies?
Absolutely.
There was never any doubt.
As a matter of fact, we received our commission and our license in Galveston, and we came up here and graduated right out of the gym, just like everybody else.
Every summer you went on a big cruise.
Right.
And it was all summer?
It wasn't just six weeks?
Oh, no, it was  well, it was
I want to say it was like 90 days, something like that, 80 to 90 days.
And you began to feel sure of your career goal?
No doubt, no doubt.
It stayed.
When I got my commission, I had to ship out because we just didn't have enough.
So when I got my license and my commission, now the license exam is, you know, that takes a week and about eight hours a day.
It's a really tough exam.
And again because of the standards that existed with this university that carried over to Galveston because we were held accountable down there for our grades.
I mean all of our
you know, all my, everything was like, it was just as if I was going to school up here, but in a different major.
There was distance involved, but that's it.
And I sort of think that's what we've done with some of these other schools that are part of the Texas A&M University system.
I don't, and of course, Galveston.
I think it's all, I don't note any difference.
And so, no, we felt like we were part of it, and it was...
You know, we were proud to wear our rings.
Just like, in fact, last night there were two youngsters sitting there that I didn't recognize, my friends, because nobody else had done it up until Randy House got up there.
And I feel very bad that I didn't now because those two twins sitting there just put their rings on yesterday.
And I probably should have mentioned that, but it didn't seem appropriate for what we were doing, so I didn't.
Those two boys had been in the Navy and were now down there going to school with their dad.
In fact, Carl, the fellow with the beard, is a retired captain of the Merchant Marines and he's teaching down there now.
Your ring, do you remember how much it cost?
Where'd you get that?
My mother paid for it.
How did you feel when you put it on?
